Maybe nourishment means we are allowing ourselves the ability to have something all to ourselves wether itâ€™s just a listing ear, or something a bit indulgent. Just something that makes us feel a sense of encouragement and a sense of filling the gaps in our being. Abide has great meditations on YouTube here, and itâ€™s a wonderful accompaniment to the yoga series for more restful sleep, and that makes almost all the difference, when the body and mind starts to feel better from yoga, and the soul has time to rest and really reflect and do what it needs to do while sleeping. I have been practicing yoga with Adriene and others for years and I think of myself as an intermediate learner. However after contracting Covid in dec 2021, I have struggled to do intermediate practices. Itâ€™s been a while since I â€œrecoveredâ€, the equivalent of testing negative, but I still suffer from shortness of breath and my body feels lacking in strength. I was only able to start this series two days ago. On the first, I collapsed and had to give myself a few more days. I now come to the mat as if this is my first time doing yoga, I try to take it easy and forget how far I was in my pre- Covid practices. What I love about this annual series and yoga in general is the sense of a possibility of new beginnings. It allows me to forget what came before and I am trying to overcome that feeling of regression because of sickness, and start again. I completed my third day today with no judgements towards myself. I feel like a â€œbeginnerâ€ again, and I am trying to embrace that. With yoga, everyday is a new beginning, and we have to meet ourselves where we are, not through some preconceived notions of beginner, intermediate, and advanced. I learned this from Adriene years ago, and I have never appreciated this more than now.

Adriene! Never apologize for singing! There are plenty of things worth apologizing for in life, but singing is not one of them! We LOVE hearing you sing! You have been a fun, relatable yoga master who seems like one of the people rather than some serious and formal stigma that can sometimes come with the public idea of what a yoga master should be. Your channel is one that is welcoming and inclusive. So keep on singing and never apologize for it! ;)

Iâ€™m so glad I signed up for Move. Prior to the pandemic I had been practicing 3-4 times a week at an intermediate level for a number of years. This was at a gym, so there were different instructors different styles at different levels of intermediate with no attempt to coordinate or design a practice structure or progression. Iâ€™m not complainingâ€”new members arrived all the time and classes needed to be accessible to allâ€”but I never had the sense that I was advancing physically or spiritually (though I did become more flexible). The pandemic disrupted my routine, like everyoneâ€™s, and I hadnâ€™t built the discipline to stick to a schedule on my own, consequently my practice devolved quickly. When I did make time it was usually for a yin classâ€”which is great, but I lost much of my ability to flow, to balance. I had found Yoga with Adriene through The NY Times and really liked it so when I heard about this 30-day plan I thought I would see if I could return to a more dedicated practice.  I am surprised already by what a difference it is making, as if there really is some kind of muscle memory both mental and physical. I try to follow the Move session with a meditation. And Iâ€™m planning to become a member of Yoga with Adriene when it has completed. Iâ€™ve tried a couple of other online yoga instructors, but they are usually focused exclusively on progressing toward more advanced physical asanas with little attention to mind or spirit. Adrieneâ€™s super balanced, warmâ€”loving, actuallyâ€”approach makes it so much more inviting to â€œshow up on the matâ€ every day. She is a marvel, an evolved being.
